{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489647"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:24:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:24:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"709"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/709"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.1,0.29,0.01,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"709"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97883"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/709"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"709"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80433"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1157"},{"type":"tags","id":"1164"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3773"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10497"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35795"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97883"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man undergoes open surgical clipping of a ruptured anterior communicating artery aneurysm. He makes good initial progress, being alert and oriented with GCS 15 and no focal neurological deficits. On the fifth post-operative day he becomes drowsy and disoriented, complaining of a new headache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 124/78 mmHg, pulse 80/min and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. He has a left-sided facial droop and 4/5 weakness of the left upper limb. His bloods results from this morning are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most likely explanation for this change in condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["De novo thromboembolic stroke","Post-haemorrhagic hydrocephalus","Delayed cerebral ischaemia","Non-convulsive seizure","Aneurysm rebleeding"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is manifesting neurological deterioration in the days following aneurysmal subarachnoid haemorrhage (SAH): differentials include complications of the haemorrhage, such as vasospasm (subsequently causing delayed cerebral ischaemia), hydrocephalus, re-bleeding, and seizure, as well as intercurrent problems such as hyponatraemia, sepsis, metabolic encephalopathy, and de novo ischaemic stroke. The non-localising features seen (confusion, reduced conscious level, headache) are common across these differentials, but the superimposed localising features (left-sided faciobrachial weakness) increase suspicion of a territorial vascular event. In this case, the most likely cause is \u003Cstrong\u003Edelayed cerebral ischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDelayed cerebral ischaemia is caused by vasospasm, believed to be triggered by blood products in the subarachnoid space irritating the abluminal surface of blood vessels with subsequent ischaemia in the corresponding cerebral tissue. Symptomatic vasospasm occurs in ~30% of SAH patients, and this patient falls within the peak risk window of 3 - 14 days post SAH. Classic clinical features include confusion and/or increased sedation, plus or minus focal phenomena including territorial motor deficits or cranial nerve palsies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERe-bleeding\u003C/strong\u003E is a catastrophic complication of untreated ruptured aneurysms that typically occurs early: a third within 3 hours, half within 6 hours. Overall, 15-20% re-bleed within 2 weeks. However, a surgically clipped intracranial aneurysm, such as in this case, has a 1.3% re-bleeding risk. Therefore, it is less likely to be the correct explanation to this patient\u0027s symptoms. \u003Cstrong\u003EHydrocephalus\u003C/strong\u003E is detected on initial imaging in ~15-20% of SAH patients, caused by extravasated blood products interfering with CSF circulation. Only 3% of patients without hydrocephalus on initial imaging go on to develop it within the first week. Up to a quarter of SAH patients have \u003Cstrong\u003Eseizures\u003C/strong\u003E at onset, and a third have delayed seizures; non-convulsive status epilepticus occurs in 3-18%. \u003Cstrong\u003EDe novo thromboembolic stroke\u003C/strong\u003E would be quite coincidental and is unlikely (n.b. the next step of workup for this patient - a CT brain with angiography and perfusion maps - is the same scan used to investigate a potential stroke and would identify this anyway).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vasospasm presents with focal and/or global neurological deterioration in the days following SAH"],"references":["Handbook of Neurosurgery. Greenberg (ed), 9th edition, 2019. Thieme. ISBN 9781684201372.","Ikram et al. Delayed Cerebral Ischemia after Subarachnoid Hemorrhage. J Stroke Cerebrovasc Dis. 2021 Aug 28;30(11):106064.","Johnston SC, Dowd CF, Higashida RT, Lawton MT, Duckwiler GR, Gress DR. Predictors of rehemorrhage after treatment of ruptured intracranial aneurysms: the Cerebral Aneurysm Rerupture After Treatment (CARAT) study. Stroke. 2008 Jan 1;39(1):120-5."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80433"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"709"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80433"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-10T10:49:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T15:16:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"709"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97883"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/131"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Subarachnoid haemorrha